00:42.820 --> 00:51.660
This is Daryl Lane and David Crews. Almost with the publication of her first novel
in 1976, C. J. Cherryh became one of the most popular science fiction writers working

00:51.660 --> 01:00.620
today. That first novel was Gate of Ivrel. Cherryh added two more books to make it
a trilogy, Well of Shiuan and Fires of Azeroth, and for Well of Shiuan she was given

01:00.620 --> 01:09.100
the John W. Campbell Award as the best new writer of the year. Cherryh has
published some 15 novels since 1976 a very quick pace. Some of her better known

01:09.100 --> 01:18.280
books include the Faded Sun trilogy, Brothers of Earth, Downbelow Station, The
Pride of Chanur, and Hunter of Worlds. In 1978 she won a Hugo Award for the short

01:18.280 --> 01:27.600
story "Cassandra". We asked Cherryh if she'd been reading science fiction since
childhood. Yes I started reading science fiction. I suppose this is about the

01:27.600 --> 01:41.460
earliest form of literature that I read. I never made a mental distinction
between science fiction fantasy uh anything of that nature because uh my parents

01:41.460 --> 01:54.540
brought it to me to read and uh I just simply regarded it as the most
interesting the reading material that I had accessible so naturally when I began

01:54.540 --> 02:04.340
turning to writing that's what I wrote. She went on to tell us why she decided to
start writing science fiction. Actually they took my television program off the

02:04.340 --> 02:17.300
air. Um our television, at that time I was 10, television hadn't been around in
private homes very long. I had just time enough to get thoroughly addicted to uh

02:17.300 --> 02:28.080
television science fiction and then it ran its course and it was gone from the
air so I in a fit of mourning and went into uh uh the bedroom picked up a tablet

02:28.080 --> 02:36.700
and pencil and started writing my own novel. Cherryh is a talented writer with a
flair for style and structure. She might have been successful in any form of

02:36.700 --> 02:45.420
writing she chose to pursue. She tells us why she didn't write other kinds of
books. Well I didn't write the other things because I didn't like them in general.

02:45.420 --> 02:57.940
Um I find that uh uh I suppose the only thing outside of science fiction that
I've ever tried my hand at writing has been mysteries um and I don't care for

02:57.940 --> 03:10.260
the modern fashion of those and I've always viewed them as a great deal more fun
to read than they are to write um mostly because you have to be extremely

03:10.260 --> 03:24.680
controlled um and I suspect that mystery writers have to know who who did it, um
and I'd rather not know the end of my book. Um the other thing that I've tried my

03:24.680 --> 03:33.940
hand at is historical fiction and I find again that's a straight jacket because
you're rather well held with what happened whether or not it makes artistic

03:33.940 --> 03:45.300
sense so um just for the sheer pleasure of writing I prefer science fiction.
Donald Wollheim the owner and editor of DAW Books discovered Cherryh when she sent

03:45.300 --> 03:57.640
him the manuscript for Gate of Ivrel. She explains why she picked Wollheim. I grew
fascinated with um with Wollheim as an editor because I had gone through my

03:57.640 --> 04:05.860
library finally after seven years of trying to sell things and I thought well
there there must be a system to this. You see I had no professional help at all

04:06.740 --> 04:16.340
and um I began searching my library to see what editor had published the
majority of uh works and writers that I liked, figuring that we might have

04:16.340 --> 04:30.940
something in common as far as taste goes uh um so I began researching Don
Wollheim to see um um um what his preferences were uh where we differed and where

04:30.940 --> 04:41.820
we were similar and uh so I began to conclude more and more that uh we were
fairly well synthetico when it came to uh to taste uh not quite the same all the

04:41.820 --> 04:51.880
way down the line but uh generally there's a broad area of overlap uh so I found
him very easy to work with. We'll have more with C. J. Cherryh next time.

