18:02.350 --> 18:11.070
This is David Crews. And Daryl Lane. One of the finest science fiction trilogies
in recent years is C.J. Cherryh's Faded Sun series. It was published in the late

18:11.070 --> 18:19.890
1970s under the titles Kesrith, Shon'Jir, and Kutath. There are few books in
science fiction that present an alien culture with the sensitivity and depth

18:19.890 --> 18:28.050
that Cherryh has given to one of the alien races in the trilogy, the Mri. The
Mri are nomadic tribesmen of the desert. They are great warriors, and space

18:28.050 --> 18:34.670
-faring races employ them as mercenaries. Cherryh says she didn't pattern the
Mri on any modern nomadic cultures, but she used her knowledge of ancient

18:34.670 --> 18:46.730
history. When I did the Faded Sun novels, which are basically a desert culture,
I did not pattern it off any modern desert culture about which I know, frankly,

18:46.970 --> 19:00.910
nothing. I patterned it strictly by taking what I know about desert survival and
earlier nomadic cultures here on Earth,

19:04.130 --> 19:17.870
contrived a biology that would work under the extreme conditions that I
postulated, and then drew elements from here and there. It's very strange that I

19:17.870 --> 19:29.750
now get letters from people that say that it very closely resembles a modern
terrestrial nomadic culture. But this is strictly a surprise to me. I suppose it

19:29.750 --> 19:46.930
just says that I knew something about the very ancient one. We asked Cherryh what
she most admired about the Mri. I think that, for one thing, about the Mri, I

19:46.930 --> 20:05.910
think I admire their steadfastness, their ability to face time itself with
tranquility, in the sense that they can take the long view, which is a thing

20:05.910 --> 20:17.250
that is absolutely necessary, in my mind, for civilized survival. In my mind, I
don't say just survival, but civilized survival. It's their ability to look down

20:17.250 --> 20:33.590
the centuries and see consequences. The Mri sense of time is a very strange
thing. A Mri always lives now, and that now is a composite of the past, current

20:33.590 --> 20:47.030
events, and the future simultaneously. They do not view time as the modern
American does, which is more or less a set of beads on the string that we can

20:47.030 --> 20:58.630
snip off any tail of the string that seems inconvenient to us. The Mri concept
of the universe is holistic. The Mri have almost been wiped out, because

20:58.630 --> 21:06.510
they've been used as pawns in an interstellar war between humans and another
alien culture, the Regal. Duncan, a human who's been partly responsible for the

21:06.510 --> 21:14.250
Mri's seemingly certain demise, is conscience-stricken at the possible end of
such a beautiful and ancient culture. His solution is to attempt to become a

21:14.250 --> 21:30.630
Mri, although it may kill him and will certainly destroy his humanity. His
final sacrifice, in a sort of a redemptive sense, is that he finally agrees that

21:30.630 --> 21:43.210
he will no longer attempt to be human, that he begins to try to be something
else. Even in that, there is a considerable hazard, because if the transition is

21:43.210 --> 21:53.890
not complete, he may end up by contaminating the culture, which to the Mri and
their way of life is a very, very serious thing. But it is a voluntary and

21:53.890 --> 21:54.790
conscious decision

21:58.050 --> 22:10.010
that effectively it is personal suicide. And he takes it because he feels
responsible for what has happened. Duncan's attempt to become a Mri is one of

22:10.010 --> 22:15.730
the most sensitive treatments of human-alien contact in science fiction. We'll
have more with C.J. Cherryh on our next program.

